{"id":"mai-tbnh","kind":"ticket","type":"feature","title":"mai search v2 — inverted index + hybrid retrieval roadmap","priority":3,"tags":["search","roadmap","architecture"],"body":"## What\n\nFuture improvements to mai search beyond the current brute-force BM25.\n\n## Context\n\nConversation with hooman 2026-04-04 after shipping mai search v1 (mai-06yi):\n\n\u003e At query time: hybrid retrieval + rerank → way fewer misses.\n\u003e https://www.anthropic.com/engineering/contextual-retrieval\n\u003e https://gokuljs.com/blogs/retrieval-from-first-principles -\u003e this too, inverted index etc\n\n## Current state (v1)\n\n- Brute-force BM25: scores every document on every query — O(N)\n- Weighted fields: title=3.0, tags=2.0, body=1.0, comments=0.5\n- \u003c10ms on 5k tickets, quality validated on trek (5192 tickets, 180MB)\n- No stemming, no inverted index, no embeddings\n- Lives in pkg/notes/search.go (265 lines), built during Index.Build()\n\n## Ideas (ordered by payoff/effort)\n\n### 1. Inverted index — O(postings) instead of O(N)\nCurrent: score every doc for every query.\nBetter: map term → [doc_ids with that term], only score candidates.\nAt 5k tickets: doesn't matter. At 50k: matters a lot.\nPure Go, no deps, maybe 50 lines on top of current code.\nReference: https://gokuljs.com/blogs/retrieval-from-first-principles\n\n### 2. Phrase matching / proximity scoring\nBM25 is bag-of-words — \"New York\" and \"York New\" score identically.\ncs (codespelunker) solves this with snippet extraction that rewards closer matches.\nCould add a proximity bonus when query terms appear within N tokens of each other.\n\n### 3. Contextual BM25 (Anthropic approach)\nPrepend LLM-generated context to each note before indexing:\n\"This ticket is about extracting the PR workflow into a separate binary as part of the plugin architecture...\"\nReduces retrieval failures by 35% per Anthropic's measurements.\nCost: one LLM call per note at index time (could cache in note metadata).\nReference: https://www.anthropic.com/engineering/contextual-retrieval\n\n### 4. Hybrid retrieval — BM25 + semantic embeddings\nBM25 for exact term matches + embeddings for semantic similarity.\n\"remote access\" matches \"VPN tunneling\" without shared keywords.\nRequires: embedding model (all-MiniLM-L6-v2 is 22MB, CPU-only).\nAdds external dep — tension with \"one Go binary, no deps\" principle.\nCould use a Go-native embedding approach or shell out.\n\n### 5. Reranking\nAfter BM25 retrieves top-150 candidates, cross-encoder rescores top-20.\nAnthropic: BM25 + contextual + reranking = 67% fewer retrieval failures.\nRequires LLM or cross-encoder at query time — latency concern.\nOnly makes sense after hybrid retrieval is in place.\n\n## Decision: stays in core\n\nSearch is a query operation on the Index, same as ls/find/context/show.\nDoes not extract to mai-search unless it grows to need persistent disk index, embedding inference, or LLM calls with their own lifecycle.\nADR from conversation with hooman 2026-04-04.\n\n## Goal\n## What\n\nFuture improvements to mai search beyond the current brute-force BM25.\n\n## Context\n\nConversation with hooman 2026-04-04 after shipping mai search v1 (mai-06yi):\n\n\u003e At query time: hybrid retrieval + rerank → way fewer misses.\n\u003e https://www.anthropic.com/engineering/contextual-retrieval\n\u003e https://gokuljs.com/blogs/retrieval-from-first-principles -\u003e this too, inverted index etc\n\n## Current state (v1)\n\n- Brute-force BM25: scores every document on every query — O(N)\n- Weighted fields: title=3.0, tags=2.0, body=1.0, comments=0.5\n- \u003c10ms on 5k tickets, quality validated on trek (5192 tickets, 180MB)\n- No stemming, no inverted index, no embeddings\n- Lives in pkg/notes/search.go (265 lines), built during Index.Build()\n\n## Ideas (ordered by payoff/effort)\n\n### 1. Inverted index — O(postings) instead of O(N)\nCurrent: score every doc for every query.\nBetter: map term → [doc_ids with that term], only scor